definition.value: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with receptors for intercellular adhesion molecule-3 (ICAM-3), such as DC-SIGN and LFA-1.
Antagonizes ribosome-mediated translation of mRNA into a polypeptide.

label.value: high molecular weight B cell growth factor receptor binding

definition.value: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the high molecular weight B cell growth factor receptor.

label.value: high molecular weight B cell growth factor receptor activity

definition.value: Combining with a high molecular weight B cell growth factor and transmitting the signal to initiate a change in cell activity.

label.value: ligand-dependent nuclear receptor transcription coactivator activity

definition.value: The function of a transcription cofactor that activates transcription in conjuction with a ligand-dependent nuclear receptor from a RNA polymerase II promoter -  does not bind DNA itself.
The function of a transcription cofactor that activates transcription in conjunction with a thyroid hormone-dependent nuclear receptor from a RNA polymerase II promoter -  does not bind DNA itself.
Combining with the urokinase plasminogen activator to initiate a change in cell activity.
Catalysis of the synthesis of free D-serine from L-serine.

Combining with neurotensin, a neuropeptide active in the central and peripheral nervous system in mammals, and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other by a mechanism independent of coupling to G proteins.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the interleukin-17E receptor.
Catalysis of the two-electron reduction of the disulfide of thioredoxins with electrons from ferredoxin involving a 4Fe-4S cluster and an adjacent active-site disulfide.
A protein complex that possesses ferredoxin - thioredoxin reductase activity.
Catalysis of the phosphorylation of fructosamine to form fructosamine-3-kinase.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with lactose, a disaccharide of glucose and galactose, the carbohydrate of milk.
Catalysis of the transfer of a formimino group from 5-formimidoyltetrahydrofolate to an acceptor molecule such as an amino acid.
Catalysis of the reaction -  5-formimidoyltetrahydrofolate + glycine -eq- (6S)-5,6,7,8-tetrahydrofolate + N-formimidoylglycine.
Catalysis of the reaction -  5-formimidoyltetrahydrofolate + L-glutamate -eq- tetrahydrofolate + N-formimidoyl-L-glutamate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  3 S-adenosyl-L-methionine(1+) -eq- 3 S-methyl-5'-thioadenosine + 3 H(+) + nicotianamine.
Catalysis of the reaction -  scytalone -eq- 1,3,8-trihydroxynaphthalene + H(2)O.
Catalysis of the reaction -  5-formimidoyltetrahydrofolate + 2 H(+) -eq- 5,10-methenyltetrahydrofolate + NH(4)(+).
A small peptide excreted by a naturally transformable bacterium (e.g. Bacillus subtilis) that transmits a signal required for the establishment of competence.
Stops, prevents or reduces the activity of a peptidase, any enzyme that catalyzes the hydrolysis peptide bonds.
The long process of a neuron that conducts nerve impulses, usually away from the cell body to the terminals and varicosities, which are sites of storage and release of neurotransmitter.

A neuron projection that has a short, tapering, often branched, morphology, receives and integrates signals from other neurons or from sensory stimuli, and conducts a nerve impulse towards the axon or the cell body. In most neurons, the impulse is conveyed from dendrites to axon via the cell body, but in some types of unipolar neuron, the impulse does not travel via the cell body.
The migrating motile tip of a growing nerve cell axon or dendrite.
Any part of a cell where non-isotropic growth takes place.

A structure composed of peptidoglycan and often chitin in addition to other materials. It usually forms perpendicular to the long axis of a cell or hypha and grows centripetally from the cell wall to the center of the cell and often functions in the compartmentalization of a cell into two daughter cells.
Catalysis of the reaction -  L-kynurenine + H2O -eq- anthranilate + L-alanine.
The cytoplasm of a host cell.
The wall surrounding a cell of a dimorphic fungus growing in the single-cell budding yeast form, in contrast to the filamentous or hyphal form.
The cell wall surrounding a fungal hypha.

label.value: chromatin silencing at silent mating-type cassette

definition.value: Repression of transcription at silent mating-type loci by alteration of the structure of chromatin.
Polarized accumulation of cytoskeletal proteins (including F-actin) and regulatory proteins in a cell. An example of this is the actin cap found in Saccharomyces cerevisiae.

An endocytic patch  that consists of an actin-containing structure found at the plasma membrane in cells -  formed of networks of branched actin filaments that lie just beneath the plasma membrane and assemble, move, and disassemble rapidly. An example of this is the actin cortical patch found in Saccharomyces cerevisiae.
The contractile fiber of smooth muscle cells.
Electron-dense region associated with a smooth muscle contractile fiber.
Catalysis of the reaction -  1D-myo-inositol 4,5-bisphosphate + H2O -eq- 1D-myo-inositol 4-phosphate + phosphate.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with hemoglobin, an oxygen carrying, conjugated protein containing four heme groups and globin.

A thin cytoplasmic bridge formed between daughter cells at the end of cytokinesis. The midbody forms where the contractile ring constricts, and may persist for some time before finally breaking to complete cytokinesis.
Catalysis of the transfer of inorganic diphosphate across a membrane.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with ankyrin, a 200 kDa cytoskeletal protein that attaches other cytoskeletal proteins to integral membrane proteins.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with spectrin, a protein that is the major constituent of the erythrocyte cytoskeletal network. It associates with band 4.1 (see band protein) and actin to form the cytoskeletal superstructure of the erythrocyte plasma membrane. It is composed of nonhomologous chains, alpha and beta, which aggregate side-to-side in an antiparallel fashion to form dimers, tetramers, and higher polymers.

A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a member of the BMP (bone morphogenetic protein) family to a receptor on the surface of a target cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the activity of any BMP receptor signaling pathway.

label.value: positive regulation of BMP signaling pathway

definition.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of BMP signaling pathway activity.

label.value: negative regulation of BMP signaling pathway

definition.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the BMP signaling pathway.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with small nucleolar RNA.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with any part of a small nucleolar ribonucleoprotein particle.
Catalysis of the reaction -  acyl-CoA + dihydrolipoamide -eq- CoA + S-acyldihydrolipoamide.

label.value: granulocyte macrophage colony-stimulating factor receptor complex

definition.value: The heterodimeric receptor for granulocyte macrophage colony-stimulating factor.
